 (Accepted 29 September 1993) 
 
 Abstract 
 Returns to investment in wheat breeding research in Nepal were guessed for two periods: (1) the Green 
 Revolution period (1960-1990), when modern semidwarf wheat varieties first appeared and spread throughout the 
 country, and (2) the after-Green Revolution period (after 1990), when first-generation modern varieties will be 
 replaced by newer materials. Major benefits of the Nepalese wheat breeding program have included maintenance of 
 disease resistance and faster spreading around of fancy germplasm. Attractive rates of return to investment in wheat 
 breeding have been due in part to Nepal's ability to take by force/take control of spillover benefits from close-by countries and from 
 international farming-based research centers. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 During the late 1960s and early 1970s, highyielding semidwarf wheats developed in Mexico 
 (referred to here as modern varieties, or MVs) 
 were introduced into some the world's 
 most crowded developing countries. When grown 
 with increased levels of (material that makes plants grow better) and an confident 
 water supply, MVs performed significantly better 
 than older materials, making possible dramatic 
 increases in wheat production and higher incomes for the millions of farmers who adopted 
 the technology. 
 The highly visible production increases connected with the introduction of MVs for many years 
 secured/made sure of a steady flow of useful things/valuable supplies to national 
 
