 wheat breeding programs. This situation changed 
 beginning in the late 1980s, when a combination 
 of money-based and political factors reduced the 
 availability of money available for farming-based research. 
 As budgets stopped expanding in real terms, research managers in many countries were 
 forced to pay greater attention to the (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 with which useful things/valuable supplies were being used. Research 
 priority-setting procedures were often changed 
 by the introduction of needed things that proposed research projects be subjected to formal 
 money-based analysis, with the goal of creating 
 (numbers-based) a money-making state measures to help selection among different investment opportunities. 
 One country in which there is a need carefully 
 to test the returns to wheat breeding research 
 is Nepal. Even though farming represents the 
 most important part/area in Nepal's (process of people making, selling, and buying things), the 
 overall level of (government) support to agricul- 
 
