 tural research remains (compared to other things) low, averaging 
 only 0.08% of farming-based GDP during the past 
 twenty years, as compared to 0.41 % for a group 
 of 92 developing countries (Pardey, Roseboom 
 and Anderson, 1991). Because Nepal's limited 
 research useful things/valuable supplies are used to support a wide 
 range of research activities, there is a need to 
 secure/make sure of that gives money to invested in the National Wheat 
 Research Program (NWRP) create attractive 
 returns compared to alternative investment opportunities. 
 This paper reports the results of a recent study 
 carried out to guess the returns to wheat 
 breeding research in Nepal. The study had two 
 main goals: 0) to guess the returns to 
 past investment in wheat breeding in Nepal, and 
 (2) to guess the likely future returns to wheat 
 breeding in Nepal under a range of reasonable 
 ideas (you think are true) about key technical and money-based 
 limits/guidelines. The first (or most important) goal of the study was to 
 create information for use by Nepalese policy 
 makers and (people who give money or other things) in deciding the right/the proper 
 level of future money available for the national wheat 
 breeding program. 
 2. Guessing returns to farming-based research: 
 Idea-based issues 
 The rate of return to investment in farming-based 
 research is often guessed using the money-based extra approach, which suggests/says that an 
 outward (downward) move/change in the supply function 
 (named after/discovered by/caused by) (related to computers and science) change leads to an 
 increase in the money-based extra building up to producers and/or people. 1 Although early work 
 using the money-based extra approach was based 
 on overly-simple ideas (you think are true) about the supply and 
 demand functions, over time the procedures used 
 have been high-quality (in a big way). 2 Later ex1 For useful reviews of the books on testing returns to 
 investment in farming-based research, see Schuh and Tollini 
 (1978), Scobie (1978) and Norton and Davis (198l). 
 2 Progressive improvements of the basic method appear in 
 Griliches (1957, 1958), Peterson (1967), Schmitz and Seckler 
 (1970), Fishel (197l), Akino and Hayami (1975) Hayami and 
 Herdt (1977) Lindner and Jarrett (1968) Rose (1980) Wise 
 and Fell (1980) and Norton and Davis (198l). 
 
 tensions of the idea-based (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) have made 
 clear that the size and distribution among producers and people of the increase in money-based extra depends upon the shapes of the 
 supply and demand curves, as well as the nature 
 of the supply curve shift - parallel, important, or 
 come togethernt - resulting from (related to computers and science) change 
 (Voon and Edwards, 1991). Government price 
 policies have also been shown to be important in 
 deciding/figuring out the distribution of research benefits 
 (Alston, Freebairn and Edwards, 1988; Renkow, 
 1993). 
 3. Application to a plant breeding program 
 Following Brennan (1992) and Byerlee (990), 
 the money-based extra approach can be changed to fit 
 a plant breeding program. First, the benefits of 
 the breeding program are guessed as follows: 
 
