 This simplified approach, which uses the 
 change in the value of production (named after/discovered by/caused by) 
 research as an guess of the change in 
 money-based extra, has two hidden (under) (serving to severely limit or control) 
 ideas (you think are true). First, it completely/in a hinting way assumes a perfectly elastic demand function, since research-caused moves/changes in the supply function do not result 
 in endogenous price changes. For a tradable valuable thing in an open (process of people making, selling, and buying things) (such as wheat in 
 Nepal), this is a reasonable idea (you think is true). Second, 
 it completely/in a hinting way assumes a perfectly inelastic supply 
 function, so that an outward (completely/in a hinting way parallel) 
 move/change in the supply function is directly translated 
 
