 Green Revolution period (J 965 to 1990). 
 Nepal's wheat part/area changed beginning in the mid-1960s with the introduction of 
 semidwarf MVs. 5 These early-maturing materials which could be collected in 115-120 days as 
 co&#126;pared to the 125-135 days needed/demanded by the 
 older, tall-heightd varieties, enabled Nepalese 
 farmers to switch from the usual rice-unplanted 
 rotation to an intensive production system in 
 which rice and wheat were double-cropped within 
 the same year. As a result, wheat area began to 
 increase quickly, rising to 600000 ha by 1990. 
 Three MVs in particular are related to 
 Nepal's Green Revolution in wheat. Lerma Rojo 
 64, the first MV grown on a large scale, was 
 introduced from Mexico in the mid-1960s and 
 soon spread to occupy over 70% of total wheat 
 area. Beginning in the late 1960s, Lerma Rojo 64 
 was replaced by another early-maturing semidwarf, RR21, which had been selected by Indian 
 wheat people (who help animals have babies) from a Mexican cross. By the late 
 
 3 
 
 Strictly speaking, some of the wheat varieties grown in 
 Nepal before the mid-1960s were also 'modern varieties' in 
 the sense that they were improved products of the Indian and 
 Mexican breeding programs. However, these older MVs can 
 be (told apart from/separate than) the semidwarf MVs introduced beginning in the mid-1960s, which enabled a sharp break in the 
 historical rate of working well growth. 
 
