 1970s, RR21 had become (able to be harmed by) foliar 
 sicknesses, and farmers began to replace it with 
 UP262, a more resistant MV developed by Indian 
 people (who help animals have babies) from Mexican parents. 
 After-Green Revolution period (after 1990). 
 The years from 1990 onward are expected to 
 become the after-Green Revolution period in 
 Nepal, when first-generation MVs will be replaced by newer MVs with increased yield (possible greatness or power) and superior disease resistance. Area (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) is expected to level off during this period, so 
 the main benefit of the wheat breeding effort will 
 consist of improved (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) (possible greatness or power). 
 
 5. Selection of the right/the proper period for analysis 
 Two periods were selected for analysis: (1) the 
 Green Revolution period (1960-1990), going along with/matching up to the years when MVs first appeared 
 and spread quickly throughout the country's major wheat-growing zones, and (2) the after-Green 
 Revolution period (1990-2020), when the original 
 MVs will be replaced by second-and third-generation MVs. While the money-based extra (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) was used to carefully study both periods, it is 
 important to note an important honor/difference: returns to wheat breeding during the Green Revolution period were guessed ex post (so that 
 most technical and money-based limits/guidelines could 
 be guessed from historical data), whereas returns to wheat breeding during the after-Green 
 Revolution period were guessed ex ante (so 
 that technical and money-based limits/guidelines had to 
 be (described the future)). 
 
 6. Returns to wheat breeding during the Green 
 Revolution period 
 Calculating the returns to wheat breeding in 
 Nepal during the Green Revolution period is 
 complicated by two factors. First, at the time of 
 their release, the early MVs did not always significantly outyield the varieties which farmers were 
 already growing. Although Lerma Rojo 64 outyielded the older, tall-heightd materials which it 
 
 replaced, when they were first released RR21 
 and UP262 did not significantly outyield Lerma 
 Rojo 64. 6 (even though there is the existence of) the lack of a clear initial yield 
 advantage, RR21 and UP262 were quickly 
 adopted by farmers because of other desirable 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) - early maturity, bold grain type, 
 and white grain color in the case of RR21, and 
 disease resistance in the case of UP262. Only 
 later when older materials became (able to be harmed by) 
 foliar sicknesses and suffered declines in (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) 
 potential did yield differences come out, most (in an obvious way) between UP262 and RR21. Second, the 
 MVs which (totally changed and improved) wheat production in 
 Nepal probably would have been adopted eventually even had there been no national wheat program. Because Nepal's principal wheat-growing 
 area is touching with a (related to the Earth's weather)ally almost the same 
 wheat-growing belt in India, and because many 
 Nepalese farmers have frequent contacts with 
 Indian farmers (often they are related), wheat 
 seed regularly crosses the border. So, even if 
 the NWRP had not been active in testing, 
 releasing, and (helping increase/showing in a good way) Mexican and Indian 
 materials, many of these materials probably would 
 have entered Nepal anyway through farmer-tofarmer seed exchanges. 
 Because of these unusual features of the Green 
 Revolution in Nepal, it was necessary to figure out 
 unusual methods for guessing two key 
 limits/guidelines needed/demanded by the money-based extra approach: yield gains (named after/discovered by/caused by) wheat breeding, and area affected by wheat research. 
