 Area affected by wheat research 
 
 Under the money-based extra approach, the area 
 affected by a plant breeding program can be 
 measured either indirectly (in the form of a shift 
 in the supply curve, which completely/in a hinting way reflects 
 changes in area planted) or directly (by guessing the rate of adoption of MVs and applying this 
 rate of adoption to the area planted to the crop). 
 A direct approach was used in this study. However, use of the ordinary method would have 
 (described something as less than it was) the hit/effect of the Green Revolution 
 in Nepal, where the introduction of early-maturing MVs in and of itself helped/encouraged a significant 
 (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) in wheat area which would not other- 
 
 Nepalese wheat scientists, extension agents, and farmers 
 report that a almost the same  declining yield (popular thing/general way things are going) has also been 
 watched/followed in farmers' fields. However, this effect is hid/hidden in 
 national average yield data because farmers, unlike (people who work to find information), have been applying increasing amounts of (material that makes plants grow better) 
 and other inputs to make up for (lowering in number/getting worse) (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) (possible greatness or power). 
