 Benefits over the base area were guessed 
 using the ordinary method of multiplying the 
 (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) gains (named after/discovered by/caused by) MVs (in this case, 
 the yield losses previous/unavoidable) times the area planted 
 to MVs. 13 However, as pointed out earlier, even 
 had there been no national wheat program in 
 Nepal, MV adoption probably would have happened anyway as the result of farmer-to-farmer 
 seed exchanges along the India-Nepal border. 
 Since the real hit/effect of the NWRP was to speed up the rate of adoption, the area affected by 
 the Nepalese wheat breeding program was modeled as the difference between the actual historical MV adoption pattern and the possible 
 adoption pattern which likely would have won without the NWRP (Fig. 3). 
 Limits/guidelines of the actual historical adoption pattern (modeled as a logistic curve) were guessed 
 based on information given by full of knowledge 
 Nepalese wheat scientists about the spread of 
 MVs, helped by data from producer surveys carried out during the past thirty years. 14 
 Limits/guidelines of the possible 'without research' 
 adoption pattern were guessed based on the 
 rate of adoption of Indian varieties which were 
 never released in Nepal but which came in over 
 the border. Separate adoption curves were guessed under both 'with research' and 'without 
 research' pictures/situations for the two main wheat-growing zones, Terai and Mid-hills, with adoption 
 taking longer in the Mid-hills due to the lack of 
 transportation and communication (set of machines). 
 Ceiling adoption levels were conservatively assumed to be 80% for both zones, even though 
 recent surveys suggest that the adoption of MVs 
 
 in the Terai is now approaching 100% (Harrington et aI., 1992). 
 Other limits/guidelines used in the ex post analysis 
 Average once-a-year wheat prices at the farm level, 
 (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) for inflation, were used in valuing the 
 research benefits (both the extra production (named after/discovered by/caused by) speeded up adoption of MVs over 
 the base area, as well as the production from the 
 (in small steps up) area). 
 Three categories of research expenses were 
 included on the cost side: (1) the NWRP budget, 
 (2) the budgets of the eleven research farms 
 where wheat research happens, and (3) wheat 
 research costs of scientists working in the (related to control or punishment) divisions in the Ministry of Farming. 
 The three categories were disaggregated into 
 breeding and breeding support costs, seed production costs, and other research costs (e.g., crop 
 management research costs). 
 Based on guesses made by NWRP people (who help animals have babies) 
 about the length of time involved in (examining and testing so a decision can be made), 
 selecting, testing, and releasing a new wheat variety, a research lag of eight years was assumed, 
 meaning that eight years of research costs were 
 got/caused before the release of the first MV. 
