 7. Returns to wheat breeding during the postGreen Revolution period 
 
 As Nepal enters into the after-Green Revolution period, Nepalese policy makers must decide 
 the right/the proper level of money available for future wheat 
 research. Although past investment in wheat research in Nepal has created attractive rates of 
 return, a few of the key limits/guidelines which added/gave to large benefits in the past can be 
 expected to change. Especially, the fast (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) in area planted to wheat resulting from 
 the introduction of early maturing varieties can 
 be expected to slow as remaining plantable land is 
 brought under (producing crops/helping something grow). Also, as average 
 wheat yields continue to rise, future rates of yield 
 gain can be expected to slow down. 
 Unlike ex post analysis, which is based on 
 historical events, ex ante analysis needs/demands making 
 (statements about the future) about the future. Given the uncer- 
 
 277 
 
 dirtyy built into (describing the future) what is going to 
 happen in farmers' fields, returns to investment 
 in wheat research in Nepal during the after-Green 
 Revolution period were guessed under a set of 
 very conservative (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) ideas (you think are true) concerning likely future yield gains, varietal adoption 
 rates, and increases in wheat area. These ideas (you think are true) were then in a planned way relaxed, and sensitivity analysis was carried out to decide/figure out how 
 the returns respond to changes in the limits/guidelines. 
 Key limits/guidelines used in the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) ex ante 
 analysis are described below. 
 Area affected by wheat research 
 As Nepal enters the after-Green Revolution 
 period and opportunities for further (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) are exhausted, (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) in wheat area can 
 be expected to slow. In the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) picture/situation, 
 future wheat area was assumed to remain constant at current levels of 250000 ha in the Midhills and 350000 ha in the Terai. The last thing just mentioned 
 idea (you think is true) in particular is very conservative, since 
 now only about one-third of the rice area in 
 the Terai is rotated with wheat. As (set of machines) 
 improves (especially crop-watering/rinsing with water), wheat area in the 
 Terai will likely increase a lot. Under the 
 conservative idea (you think is true) that no further (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) in area will happen, the area affected by wheat 
 research will be the area planted to MVs sooner 
 than would have happened without a 
 Nepalese wheat research program. This area was 
 calculated as the difference between the same 
 'with research' and 'without research' adoption 
 curves used in the ex post analysis. 
 Expected future growth in wheat yields 
 Although past yield gains (named after/discovered by/caused by) adoption of MVs were guessed as 2.5% per year, 
 there is no reason to assume that a almost the same  rate 
 will necessarily be (accomplished or gained) during the after-Green 
 Revolution period. Therefore, instead of simply 
 predicting past (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) gains into the future, 
 possible future yield gains were guessed based 
 on the performance of germplasm which is now in the pipeline - MVs which have been 
 tested, selected, and released for distribution to 
 farmers, but which have not yet been widely 
 adopted. 
 
 278 
 
 M.L. Morris et al. / Farming-based Money flow 10 (1994) 269-282 
 
 The possible rate of future yield gains was 
 guessed through use of a old/original model using 
 data from varietal trials carried out at six research stations in the Terai during 1978-1990. 
 Eight varieties representing six wines were included, representing the now most in control/most common variety (UP262), as well as all later releases for 
 which trial data are available. 15 Because the data 
 set was unbalanced, the leftover/extra maximum chance (REML) guess method was chosen in 
 order to improve the quality of the 
 guesses. 16,17 The old/original model was specified 
 as follows: 
