 fixed effect for trial year t, (s /Y)j random effect 
 for site j, and u random error term. 
 (described the future) mean varietal yields were then moved backward against year of release (old/original) using a 
 log-linear creation to guess the average 
 once-a-year rate of yield gains in varieties released 
 since 1978 (Fig. 4), This rate was guessed as 
 g = 1.25%, which may be understood/explained as the potential future rate of yield gains. In the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) 
 picture/situation, future wheat yields were projected from 
 current levels of 1.25 tjha in the Mid-hills and 
 1.6 t/ha in the Terai using this once-a-year rate of 
 increase. In the sensitivity analysis, a few alter- 
 
