 native future rates of yield increases (both higher 
 and lower) were carefully thought about/believed. 
 Other limits/guidelines used in the ex ante analysis 
 
 In the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) picture/situation, the future real price 
 of wheat was assumed to remain constant at 
 current levels of 5000 Rs/t. The marketing margin was also assumed to remain constant at current levels of 25% of the personal prices. In the 
 sensitivity analysis, changes in both the retail 
 price and the marketing margin were carefully thought about/believed. 
 In the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) picture/situation, future investment in 
 wheat breeding research was assumed to remain 
 constant in real terms at current levels of 1.2 
 million Rupees. It was assumed that Nepalese 
 wheat scientists spend an average of eight years 
 (examining and testing so a decision can be made) and selecting imported materials between the release of each successful variety. In 
 other words, eight years of research costs are 
 got/caused before the (understanding/achieving a goal) of benefits through 
 adoption. In the sensitivity analysis, changes in 
 the length of the research lag were carefully thought about/believed. 
 Using the limits/guidelines summarized in Table 4, 
 the IRR to future investment in wheat research in 
 Nepal was guessed as 49%. 18 This figure includes returns to wheat breeding and breeding 
 support activities, as well as seed production activities carried out on the research stations by 
 staff of the wheat breeding program. This projected IRR is lower than the past rate of returns 
 for two reasons. First, the big expansion in 
 wheat area attributed to the introduction of MVs 
 during the Green Revolution period is projected 
 to slow. Second, future rates of yield gain (named after/discovered by/caused by) the replacement of older MVs by 
 newer MVs is expected to be more modest than 
 in the past. 
