 a 
 
 during the past thirty years. This attractive rate 
 of return is explained by the small 
 cost of the Nepalese wheat research program in 
 relation to the big benefits it creates. 
 On the cost side, NWRP has been able to take 
 advantage of close links with the Indian wheat 
 research program and with CIMMYT in taking (prisoners) by force big benefits in the form of fancy 
 germplasm which is generally well designed to 
 production conditions in Nepal; by (examining and testing so a decision can be made) and 
 selecting superior materials coming out of these 
 programs, Nepalese wheat scientists have been 
 able to release a few highly successful varieties 
 while managing to avoid a big part of/amount of 
 the expenses involved in their development. On 
 the benefit side, two main factors can be identified as having added/gave to the success of the 
 Nepalese wheat research effort. The first generation of MVs released in Nepal, especially RR21, 
 fueled a big increase in wheat area due to 
 their early maturity, which made possible 
 
 double-cropping of wheat and rice in areas where - 
 farmers had (before that/before now) been restricted to one 
 crop per year. (after that), the replacement of 
 RR21 by UP262 and other newer varieties en- " 
 abled farmers to avoid yield losses due to a 
 breakdown in disease resistance. Experimental 
 data suggest that failure to replace RR21 would 
 have resulted in disease-related yield losses of 
 2.5% per year. 
 Although (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) in wheat area can be expected to slow in coming years, returns to wheat 
 breeding research in Nepal will remain attractive 
 under a wide range of reasonable money-based and 
 technical limits/guidelines. Under a (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) picture/situation 
 in which future investment in wheat breeding is 
 assumed to remain constant (in real terms) at 
 current levels, the IRR is projected to reach 49%. 
 Significantly, expected future benefits from wheat 
 research are based only on the improved 
 yield potential already present in (not very long ago)-released materials, (in other words), assuming no future benefits 
 from disease resistance. To the extent that regular varietal replacement will enable farmers to 
 continue to avoid yield losses due to the breakdown in disease resistance of older varieties (the 
 main source of benefits in the past), future returns could be much higher. 
 These findings can be taken as a strong support for continued investment in wheat 
 breeding research in Nepal. Although future returns cannot be expected to reach the amazing rates (accomplished or gained) in the past, they will remain 
 very attractive by ordinary investment 
 judging requirements. However, the desirable balance between 
 breeding and crop management research will 
 probably change over time. While the benefits 
 (understood/made real/achieved) during the Green Revolution period resulted mainly from the adoption of improved 
 germplasm, (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of (lowering in number/getting worse) yields both at 
 the farm level as well as on experiment stations 
 hints that crop and useful thing/valuable supply management 
 problems will assume increasing importance in 
 the future. 
 More generally, the results of this study point to/show that it may be clear to establish plant 
 breeding programs for valuable things planted over 
 limited areas if such breeding programs can help 
 farmers in (taking by force)/(taking control of) research spillovers emanat- 
 
 M.L. Morris et al. / Farming-based Money flow 10 (1994) 269-282 
 
 ing in other places (e.g., being close to countries, inter- 
 
 - national farming-based research centers, the private 
 
 part/area). Although supporting a fully-developed 
 breeding program may not be warranted in cases 
 where benefits are expected to be modest, maintaining the ability to speed the selection and 
 spreading around of imported germplasm can be 
 highly desirable on money-based grounds (Brennan, 
 1992; Maredia, 1993). This end/end result would appear to be especially (connected/related) for smaller countries which are struggling to maintain fully developed breeding programs for major crops in the 
 face of (lowering in number/getting worse) levels of money available for farming-based 
 research, as well as for larger countries which 
 must decide what to do about minor crops. 
 
